<table id="_ctl2_pnlModuleContent" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%"><tr><td>
	
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 width="100%" border=0 summary="Design Table">
  <TR vAlign=top>
    <TD id="_ctl2_HtmlHolder" class="Normal"><TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Air-Elemental.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Air</H3>
<P>Consisting solely of air, this elemental is the best at avoiding and mitigating melee damage.&nbsp; In general, Air pets have lower health than Earth or Water but make up a bit for this lack of health by taking less damage while fighting.</P>
<P>The innate ability of Air is to stun its opponent.&nbsp; Stuns are an effective means of reducing its target&#8217;s ability to cast spells and to deliver damage via melee.&nbsp; At levels 49 and below, the pet casts the stun <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=967&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Air Elemental Attack</A>. At levels 53 and above, the pet casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=1020&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Air Elemental Strike</A> which adds 10 + pet level in damage.&nbsp; Stuns at all levels have a duration of 3 seconds&nbsp; Air pets cast their attack once every 12 seconds.</P>
<P>Air has very high resistance to cold-based spells.&nbsp; The pet also has the innate ability to turn itself invisible when not in combat.&nbsp; This can be a bit of a hassle at lower levels when the magician must cast See Invisible often just to see the pet.</P>
<P>This pet is best-used against casters (as the stun interrupts channeling), but is versatile enough to be used in light tanking situations.&nbsp; Air gets better at tanking as it increases in level.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Earth-Elemental.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Earth</H3>
<P>Comprised of rock and mud, the Earth elemental is the hardiest of pets.&nbsp; At all levels earth has the highest health of any of the 4 elementals.&nbsp; This constitution comes at a price.&nbsp; The slow nature of Earth means it is less adept at avoiding and mitigating damage.&nbsp; Simply put, Earth is tanking pet &#8211; able to dish out and take melee damage.</P>
<P>The earth pet&#8217;s innate ability is to root its opponent.&nbsp; At levels 49 and below, the pet roots via a spell: <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=969&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Earth Elemental Attack</A>.&nbsp; At levels 51 and 57 the pet instead casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=1022&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Earth Elemental Strike</A>, which adds 10 + pet level in damage to the root.&nbsp; The level 65 pet casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=3193&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Earth Elemental Strike 2</A>, which includes a -30 resist modifier that makes the root a lot more likely to hold.&nbsp; Earth pets cast their spells once every six seconds.</P>
<P>Earth has very high natural resistance to disease-based spells.</P>
<P>The earth pet shines against targets that melee &#8211; especially slow, heavy hitters&#8230;and of course, rats and other disease-based monsters.&nbsp; Root is extremely handy and can even be used as a way to root mobs away from combat if you are otherwise engaged.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Fire-Elemental.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Fire</H3>
<P>As you might imagine, elementals comprised of Fire are focused primarily on attack.&nbsp; The fire elemental has low health, but ultimately has the potential for dealing more total damage than any of the 4 elemental types.&nbsp; </P>
<P>The innate ability of the Fire elemental is two-fold.&nbsp; It both attacks with and defends itself with fire-based magic.&nbsp; At levels 49 and below, Fire uses a self-damage shield (<A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=927&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Fire Elemental Aura</A>) that deals exactly 2 + pet level damage to an attacker every time the pet is hit.&nbsp; The pet uses <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=966&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Fire Elemental Attack</A> for 1 + pet level damage. At levels 52 and above, Fire pets change completely, taking on a Wizard model and correspondingly, a Wizard&#8217;s spell book and poor melee. Fire pets cast their spells once every six seconds.</P>
<P>Fire has very high natural resistance to fire-based spells.</P>
<P>Fire pets shine at low levels &#8211; especially against fast, but light-hitting mobs.&nbsp; Such targets tend to burn themselves to death on the pet&#8217;s damage shield.&nbsp; At higher levels, the wizard model is poorly implemented, significantly reducing this pet&#8217;s usefulness.&nbsp; However, as this pet will use the wizard stun line, it can be useful in certain situations.&nbsp; High level fire pets are perhaps the most debated in terms of their utility.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Water-Elemental.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Water</H3>
<P>Water may sound like a relatively harmless element, but the Water elemental is one of the most used at all levels.&nbsp; This elemental is a decent damage-dealer both via melee and magic.&nbsp; Having no particular strength and therefore no particular weakness, Water is an average pet, with utility in nearly all situations.&nbsp; Although Water has less hit points than Earth, it avoids and mitigates damage better.</P>
<P>The innate ability of the Water elemental is to use cold-based magic.&nbsp; At levels 49 and below, the pet casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=968&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Water Elemental Attack</A> for 1 + pet level damage.&nbsp; At levels 54 and above the pet casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=1021&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Water Elemental Strike</A> for (2 x pet level) + 20 damage. &nbsp;At levels 54 and above, the pet gains the ability to backstab when behind its target.&nbsp; Water pets cast their spells once every six seconds.</P>
<P>Water has very high natural resistance to poison.</P>
<P>The water pet shines at low levels against most targets &#8211; especially those that have poison-based attacks.&nbsp; At higher levels, water pets shine when they can forgo tanking and take up a position behind their target.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD>&nbsp;<IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Epic-Elemental.gif" width=216 border=0></TD>
<TD>
<H3>Epic</H3>
<P>Stories are told of Magi&#8217;kot&#8230;a great magician that went insane attempting to master all 4 elements with the hope of commanding an elemental of combined power.&nbsp; <I>[In truth, Magi&#8217;kot went crazy trying to convince the powers that be that magicians need more defensive ability in exchange for the relative loss of comparative offense in the Planes of Power.&nbsp; In fact, you will need to collect some of his shredded pleas for consideration as part of the epic quest.&nbsp; Alas, poor Magi'kot.&nbsp; I knew him well.&nbsp; Calliav agreed to take up the cause.&nbsp; We're all hoping he maintains his sanity.]</I>&nbsp; If you ignore the issues with our class and focus on mastering the elements, perhaps you will one day manifest the elemental being known as the Epic.</P>
<P>Although the Epic pet appears to be a larger version of the Air elemental, its abilities far exceed Air.&nbsp; The Epic has more hit points and does significantly more damage than any other class of elemental for its level (which is always level 49, by the way).&nbsp; Borrowing from Fire, casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=847&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Aura of Elemental Mastery</A>, a self-damage shield for 50 points.&nbsp; Borrowing from Air, the Epic casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=848&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Elemental Mastery Strike</A>, a stun with 84 points of damage every 12 seconds.&nbsp; And finally the pet procs <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=849&amp;source=Live" target=_blank>Elemental Mastery Blast</A> randomly for 143 points of damage.&nbsp; This pet also taunts quite effectively.</P>
<P>This pet shines against any target of comparable level.&nbsp; If a magician is between levels 50 and 60, it is very likely this pet will be used almost exclusively.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Monster-Summoning.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Monster</H3>
<P>It&#8217;s fairly well-known that monsters sit in a waiting room while they&#8217;re on-call.&nbsp; As a magician, you can interrupt this little coffee break and make a random monster get right to work&#8230;for you!</P>
<P>The Monster Summoning line of spells levels I &#8211; III are more for entertainment these days than for any real use.&nbsp; Monster pets look like a random non-playable race from the zone in which the spell is cast and are identical in behavior to an elemental.&nbsp; Monsters I &#8211; III have hit points between typically between water and earth and cast random elemental attack spells.&nbsp; In addition to these spells, monsters use their claws (via <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=812&amp;source=Live">SumMonsterAttack</A>) for 1 + pet level in damage. </P>
<P>Monster Summoning IV is a vast improvement over the previous three.&nbsp; This pet casts a stun similar to Air (<A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=4969&amp;source=Live">Bull Rush</A>) as well as a defensive spell called <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=4970&amp;source=Live">Prism Strike</A> which does 1 point of damage and automatically casts <A href="http://lucy.allakhazam.com/spell.html?id=5127&amp;source=Live">Prism Skin</A>.&nbsp; This latter spell completely absorbs any one hit on the pet (melee or magic) before it dissipates and must be recast.&nbsp; </P>
<P>Given this defensive ability, MS4 is ideal for raid situations.&nbsp; The rune greatly increases the pet&#8217;s survivability against boss mob AE spells.</P><TD></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
<BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Decoy.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Dyzil's Deafening Decoy</H3>
<P>This special purpose pet, which has the look of a fire elemental, is based on a novel idea -- create a pet that's sole purpose is to tank multiple mobs at once.&nbsp; Thanks to an AE taunt spell, this pet is fairly effective at making mobs hate it.&nbsp; Thanks to high hit points, this pet can take a bit of a beating.</P>
<P>The decoy is fairly effective at distracting mobs while the group evacs out (or runs for the zone).&nbsp; Say your puller has a train incoming.&nbsp; A decoy might be used distract the train (which has very little aggro against the group) rather quickly.&nbsp; While the trains kills the decoy, you have a bit of time to put Plan B into action.&nbsp; Back in my mid-50s, I used the pet a few times in this type of situation &#8211; it never failed to save us a death ... and we never failed to run for the hills leaving it to die.&nbsp; (Keep in mind that if the group has attacked a given mob, it will take the Decoy some time to build up enough aggro for that mob to switch onto it).</P>
<P>This pet follows all pet commands, just as any other pet would, but remember: the pet casts an AE taunt.&nbsp; </P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE><BR>
<HR id=null>
<BR>
<TABLE cellSpacing=0 cellPadding=0 border=0>
<TBODY>
<TR>
<TD><IMG height=360 src="/mageportal/Portals/57ad7180-c5e7-49f5-b282-c6475cdb7ee7/Rage-of-Zomm.gif" width=216 border=0>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD>
<H3>Rage of Zomm</H3>
<P><I>Have you ever met a big guy named Tiny?&nbsp; Ironic names are funny, most of the time.&nbsp; Rage of Zomm is a similar inside joke.&nbsp; As the lore of Nenelar goes, Zomm spent years researching the summoning of an elemental that would sacrifice all of the defensive capabilities of an Earth pet for a superior offensive ability.&nbsp; He only partially succeeded.&nbsp; </I></P>
<P><I>True to Zomm's plan, Rage of Zomm has very few hitpoints and no means of avoiding damage. Most mobs will kill it in a single hit.&nbsp; However, the pet has only slightly improved melee skills.&nbsp; Further, since the pet cannot be equipped with summoned gear that is readily available from higher level magicians, it actually does less damage than pet of similar level.&nbsp; </I></P>
<P><I>As you might have guessed, Zomm did not survive his first combat encounter.&nbsp; Perhaps this is why researchers are rarely generals.&nbsp; And so, we're left with the pet that carries his name to this day.</I></P>
<P>Rage of Zomm behaves quite a bit differently than other pets.&nbsp; Prior to summoning the pet, you need to have a target that you intend the pet to attack.&nbsp; Once summoned the pet will immediately attack this target.&nbsp; While the pet is alive, you may add additional mobs to its hate list using /pet attack and it will attack them all in turn.&nbsp; However, should the pet's hate list be cleared at any point, it will vanish.</P>
<P>Since no pet will accept trades while it is in combat, you will not be able to give this pet any gear.&nbsp; If you attempt to back the pet off in order to hand it an item, it will vanish.&nbsp; There is a bit of a trick in which you can have an item on your cursor while summoning.&nbsp; When the pet appears, click to trade as quickly as possible.&nbsp; You may catch the server with the trade prior to the pet initiating its attack.&nbsp; Although the pet will proceed with the planned attack, the trade dialog will stay open as long as the pet stays within trade range of you.&nbsp; This isn't really a tactic that makes a difference.&nbsp; Mages of the level to use this pet cannot summon the 61+ weapons that make this tactic worthwhile.&nbsp; Mages 61+ have no reason to use this pet ... and if they did, the mana investment in weapons would be better spent on damage spells.</P>
<P>While I'm a bit critical of the pet, it did have a use back when it was first released. Pets used to be a real risk on dungeon crawls due to poor pathing and proximity aggro.&nbsp; Now that pets are no longer aggro by default, this advantage is greatly reduced.&nbsp; Today, this pet is less a pet and more akin to a damage over time spell.&nbsp; Zomm didn't realize that and now he's dead.</P></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></TD>
	</TR></TABLE>

